"""
MKT Christ Commentary — Jeremiah chapters 31–32
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-jeremiah-31-32.py

Key decisions:
- Jer 31 is the most explicitly christological chapter in the OT; commentary is denser
- Jer 31:31 already present; script adds all other missing verses (merge_comm skips existing)
- Jer 31:15 classified direct (Matt 2:18 explicit citation)
- Jer 31:22 treated as pointing to new-creation reversal, not allegorized as virgin birth
- Jer 32:40 &quot;everlasting covenant&quot; classified as direct type anticipating Heb 13:20
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

NEW = {
"31": {
"1": "<p>The opening oracle — <strong>&quot;at that time&quot; I will be the God of all the clans of Israel and they will be my people</strong> — uses the eschatological time-marker <em>baʿet hahiʿ</em> to signal that what follows transcends the immediate historical moment. The covenant formula &quot;I will be their God and they will be my people&quot; runs from the Sinai narrative (Exod 6:7) through Jeremiah to its NT fulfillment: Revelation 21:3 declares, &quot;Behold, the dwelling of God is with man. He will dwell with them and they will be his people, and God himself will be with them as their God.&quot; Christ's incarnation is the hinge on which the covenant formula passes from promise to fulfillment.</p>",
"2": "<p>The recollection of <strong>finding grace in the wilderness</strong> — Israel going to its resting place, YHWH appearing from afar — grounds the new-covenant hope in the original Exodus pattern. The wilderness-grace motif recurs in the NT: John the Baptist (Matt 3:1-3) appears in the wilderness as the voice preparing the way; Jesus himself is led into the wilderness (Matt 4:1) and emerges to begin his redemptive mission. Every new act of divine grace follows the Exodus pattern: wilderness first, then the rest of the promised land.</p>",
"3": "<p><strong>I have loved you with an everlasting love; therefore I have drawn you with lovingkindness</strong> — the declaration of <em>ʾahavat ʿolam</em> (everlasting love) and <em>ḥesed</em> (covenant loyalty). Paul's argument in Romans 8:38-39 is the NT counterpart: nothing can separate us from the love of God in Christ Jesus. The &quot;everlasting love&quot; that Jeremiah announces as the foundation of the new-covenant hope is precisely the love that Christ embodies and enacts in his incarnation and death (John 13:1: &quot;having loved his own... he loved them to the end&quot;).</p>",
"4": "<p>The promise to <strong>build you again, O virgin Israel</strong>, so that she takes up her tambourines and dances — the image of the restored community as rebuilt and rejoicing. Revelation 19:7-9 presents the eschatological counterpart: the wedding of the Lamb where the bride has made herself ready. The virgin Israel who dances with tambourines is a type of the church presented as a pure bride to Christ (2 Cor 11:2; Eph 5:27). The rebuilding of the community anticipates the building of the church Christ promises (Matt 16:18).</p>",
"5": "<p>The planting of <strong>vineyards on the mountains of Samaria</strong> and eating their fruit — the restoration of the northern kingdom — points to the eschatological gathering that includes both Israel and Judah. Jesus's parable of the vineyard (Matt 20:1-16; 21:28-41) uses vine-planting as the image of God's kingdom project. The vine imagery culminates in John 15:1: &quot;I am the true vine&quot; — Christ himself is the vineyard that Israel's planting anticipated, and through him all nations share in the fruit.</p>",
"6": "<p>The promise that <strong>watchmen in Ephraim will call out: Rise and let us go up to Zion to YHWH our God</strong> — the northern tribes returning to worship in Jerusalem — anticipates the gathering of all Israel under one shepherd. Jesus presents himself as the good shepherd who gathers the scattered sheep (John 10:16: &quot;I have other sheep not of this fold; I must bring them also&quot;). The call from Ephraim to go up to Zion is fulfilled when the Gentiles and dispersed Israel are gathered into the one flock under Christ, the one shepherd.</p>",
"7": "<p>The command to <strong>shout for Jacob with joy, rejoice over the chief of the nations</strong> — the nations called to celebrate Israel's restoration — is an eschatological jubilee. The NT presents the ultimate jubilee as Christ's redemption: Luke 4:18-19, where Jesus reads from Isaiah 61 and announces the year of the Lord's favor, declares the jubilee Christ inaugurates. The nations shouting for joy over Jacob finds its fulfillment in the nations rejoicing in the gospel (Rom 15:10-12, citing Deut 32:43 and Ps 117:1).</p>",
"8": "<p>YHWH gathering his people from <strong>the north country and from the ends of the earth</strong> — including the blind, the lame, the pregnant, and the nursing mother — is the great eschatological ingathering. Jesus's healing of the blind (Matt 9:27-31; Mark 10:46-52; John 9) and the lame (Mark 2:1-12; John 5:1-15) are the inaugurated signs of this gathering. Isaiah 35:5-6 (the blind see, the lame leap) and Luke 7:22 (Jesus's answer to John the Baptist) establish that the messianic era is marked by precisely these reversals. Christ's healing ministry is the advance sign of this worldwide gathering.</p>",
"9": "<p>The promise that <strong>they shall come with weeping and with pleas for mercy; I will lead them by a straight way</strong>, for <strong>I am a father to Israel, and Ephraim is my firstborn</strong> — the divine fatherhood and the return of the lost son. Jesus's parable of the prodigal son (Luke 15:11-32) draws directly on this imagery: the returning son comes in weeping penitence; the father runs to him and restores him. The explicit affirmation &quot;I am a father to Israel&quot; is the theological ground for Jesus's teaching about the Father's love for returning sinners. The &quot;straight way&quot; (<em>derek yashar</em>) is the path of restoration that Jesus himself claims to be (John 14:6).</p>",
"10": "<p>The nations called to hear — <strong>He who scattered Israel will gather him and will keep him as a shepherd keeps his flock</strong> — is the divine shepherd promise. Ezekiel 34 develops this extensively; John 10 declares its fulfillment in Christ. The scatter-and-gather movement of divine judgment followed by divine compassion is resolved permanently in Christ's death and resurrection: the one who &quot;was scattered&quot; across the nations through judgment is gathered into the one body through the Spirit (1 Cor 12:13; Eph 2:14-16). The nations hearing of the shepherd's work anticipates the Gentile mission.</p>",
"11": "<p>YHWH <strong>ransoming Jacob and redeeming him from hands too strong for him</strong> — the language of <em>padah</em> (ransom) and <em>gaʾal</em> (redeem) is the vocabulary of Exodus deliverance. Paul applies both to Christ's atoning work: &quot;you were bought with a price&quot; (1 Cor 6:20, using <em>agorazō</em>, the Greek equivalent of <em>padah</em>); &quot;our great God and Savior Jesus Christ, who gave himself for us to redeem us&quot; (Titus 2:13-14, using <em>lytroō</em>, equivalent of <em>gaʾal</em>). The ransom and redemption from forces too strong for humanity finds its ultimate fulfillment in Christ's victory over sin and death.</p>",
"12": "<p>The people coming to <strong>shout for joy on the heights of Zion, radiant over YHWH's goodness — grain, wine, oil, young animals</strong> — the eschatological feast of abundance. This is the great banquet image that Jesus uses for the kingdom (Matt 8:11: &quot;many will come from east and west and recline at table with Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob in the kingdom of heaven&quot;; Luke 14:15-24). The grain, wine, and oil that mark covenant blessing become in the NT the eschatological feast where Christ himself is the host and bread (John 6:35; 1 Cor 11:26).</p>",
"13": "<p>The promise that <strong>the virgin shall rejoice in the dance, and the young men and the old together; I will turn their mourning into joy, give them gladness instead of sorrow</strong> — the reversal of mourning is the eschatological sign. Jesus explicitly fulfills this: at the wedding of Cana (John 2:1-11) he transforms the water of purification into wine of celebration; at Nain (Luke 7:13-15) he stops a funeral procession and restores the son to his mother. The pattern culminates in Revelation 21:4: &quot;he will wipe away every tear from their eyes.&quot; The eschatological joy-replacement is a work Christ performs in anticipation and will complete at the end.</p>",
"14": "<p>The priests <strong>filled with abundance, and my people satisfied with my goodness</strong> — the satiation of both priestly service and common life. The NT presents Christ as the one who fills all things (Eph 1:23; 4:10). The priest-satisfaction that Jeremiah promises finds its fulfillment in Christ's high-priestly ministry (Heb 7:25-27): he makes continual intercession, is himself the unblemished offering, and guarantees a covenant that provides permanent access to YHWH's goodness. The priestly office and the people's satisfaction are both fulfilled in the one priest who is also the sacrifice.</p>",
"15": "<p>A <strong>direct prophecy</strong>: <strong>&quot;A voice was heard in Ramah, lamentation and bitter weeping. Rachel is weeping for her children; she refuses to be comforted for her children, because they are no more.&quot;</strong> Matthew 2:18 cites this verse explicitly as fulfilled in Herod's massacre of the male infants of Bethlehem (Matt 2:16-18). The typological logic is that the sorrow which accompanied Israel's exile (Ramah was the deportation staging point, 1 Sam 10:2) is recapitulated in the grief that surrounds Christ's birth. The infant Christ escapes; the children of Bethlehem do not — they share in the pattern of innocent suffering that characterizes the pre-resurrection age and points to the one innocent sufferer who bears it fully.</p>",
"16": "<p>YHWH's word to Rachel — <strong>keep your voice from weeping and your eyes from tears, for your work will be rewarded; they will return from the land of the enemy</strong> — is the divine word of hope spoken into inconsolable grief. This is the pattern of the resurrection: against all visible evidence, the divine word promises return from the land of death. Jesus speaks similar words: &quot;Do not weep&quot; (Luke 7:13; 8:52); &quot;your brother will rise again&quot; (John 11:23). The divine refusal to let grief be the final word is the precursor to the Easter proclamation.</p>",
"17": "<p>The promise — <strong>there is hope for your future; your children shall return to their own territory</strong> — is the covenant guarantee against despair. Hebrews 6:19 calls hope &quot;an anchor for the soul, sure and steadfast, entering into the inner place behind the curtain&quot; — Christ as the high priest who has entered the heavenly sanctuary guarantees the future hope. The children returning to their own territory finds its NT counterpart in the promise that the meek shall inherit the earth (Matt 5:5) and that Christ's people are heirs of God and fellow heirs with Christ (Rom 8:17).</p>",
"18": "<p>Ephraim's confession — <strong>I was like an untrained calf; turn me that I may be turned, for you are YHWH my God</strong> — is the prayer of the one who recognizes their incapacity for self-correction and appeals entirely to divine action. The image of the untrained calf is the image of human nature apart from grace. Paul describes the same condition in Romans 7:18: &quot;I can will what is right but I cannot do it.&quot; The prayer &quot;turn me that I may be turned&quot; is the prayer for regeneration — the divine initiative that the NT identifies with the Spirit's work (Titus 3:5; John 3:5-8).</p>",
"19": "<p>Ephraim's further confession — <strong>after I turned, I was sorry; after I was instructed, I struck my thigh; I was ashamed and also humiliated, because I bore the disgrace of my youth</strong> — is the pattern of genuine contrition. The shame and humiliation of Ephraim's confession is the mirror of the shame language of the NT: Paul says believers are not ashamed of the gospel (Rom 1:16) because the shame of sin has been transferred to Christ (Heb 12:2: &quot;despising the shame&quot;; 2 Cor 5:21). Genuine repentance involves this reckoning with the full weight of past dishonor, which Christ's cross definitively covers.</p>",
"20": "<p>YHWH's response — <strong>Is Ephraim my dear son? Is he a darling child? For as often as I speak against him, I do remember him still. Therefore my heart yearns for him; I will surely have compassion on him</strong> — is one of the most tender divine self-disclosures in the OT. The divine heart that &quot;yearns&quot; (<em>hamu meʿai</em>, literally &quot;my innards are stirred&quot;) is the deep compassion that Jesus embodies in the Gospels: &quot;when he saw the crowds, he had compassion on them&quot; (Matt 9:36; using <em>splanchnizomai</em>, the visceral-compassion word). The father's compassion in the prodigal son parable (Luke 15:20) directly echoes this verse.</p>",
"21": "<p>The call to <strong>set up waymarks, make signposts; consider well the highway, the road by which you went</strong> — the returning exiles to mark the road home. The NT presents Christ himself as the road: &quot;I am the way, the truth, and the life&quot; (John 14:6). The &quot;waymarks&quot; and &quot;signposts&quot; of the prophetic tradition — all the types, shadows, and direct promises pointing toward Christ — are the signposts along the highway that leads to the Father. Hebrews 11 presents the whole of OT history as a path-marking toward the &quot;better country&quot; whose builder and maker is God.</p>",
"22": "<p>The enigmatic sign — <strong>YHWH has created a new thing on the earth: a woman encompasses a man</strong> (<em>neqevah tesovev gaver</em>) — has generated many interpretations. The most defensible reading is that it announces a radical reversal of the social order: the exile feminized and weakened Israel (&quot;woman&quot;); the restoration will give Israel such security and vigor that the woman protects the man rather than fleeing — a reversal of the typical ancient world's vulnerability. At the deepest canonical level, the &quot;new thing&quot; (<em>beritah ḥadashah</em>) points to the new creation Christ inaugurates (2 Cor 5:17: &quot;if anyone is in Christ, there is a new creation&quot;). The unprecedented divine act that reverses normal categories is the pattern of the incarnation itself.</p>",
"23": "<p>The restoration promise — <strong>they will use this speech in the land of Judah and in its cities when I restore their fortunes: &quot;YHWH bless you, O habitation of righteousness, O holy mountain&quot;</strong> — is the picture of the community greeting the land as righteous and holy after judgment and exile. The NT applies &quot;righteousness&quot; and &quot;holiness&quot; christologically: Christ is our righteousness (1 Cor 1:30; 2 Cor 5:21) and the one who sanctifies (Heb 2:11; 13:12). The restored community that speaks of righteousness and holiness as the character of its land finds its ultimate fulfillment in the new Jerusalem described in Revelation 21:27 — &quot;nothing unclean will ever enter it.&quot;</p>",
"24": "<p>The promise that <strong>farmers and those who wander with their flocks</strong> will live together in Judah — the reunification of agricultural and pastoral lifestyles in the land — represents the end of the exile's fragmentation. The NT vision of unity in Christ cuts across social and economic divisions: Galatians 3:28 (&quot;neither Jew nor Greek, slave nor free, male and female&quot;); Colossians 3:11. The eschatological unity of the restored community is a pattern that anticipates the unity Christ creates in his body, where formerly divided communities share one life.</p>",
"25": "<p>YHWH's declaration — <strong>I will satisfy the weary soul, and every languishing soul I will replenish</strong> — is a direct anticipation of Jesus's invitation: &quot;Come to me, all who labor and are heavy laden, and I will give you rest&quot; (Matt 11:28). The weary and languishing soul that Jeremiah presents as the object of divine satiation is precisely the condition of those to whom Jesus directs his call. The satisfaction YHWH promises is the rest Christ provides — not merely comfort but genuine renewal of the exhausted soul by the one who is himself rest (Heb 4:9-10).</p>",
"26": "<p>The mysterious parenthetical — <strong>at this I awoke and looked, and my sleep was pleasant to me</strong> — marks the dream-reception of this prophecy. The sleep and waking frame suggests the vision of restoration was given in a dream-like state, a mode of revelation prominent in the OT (Gen 28:10-17; Dan 7:1). The NT fulfillment of this prophetic vision is not a vision but a reality: what Jeremiah received as a dream-vision, the apostles witnessed in the flesh. John 1:14 (&quot;we beheld his glory&quot;) is the waking counterpart to Jeremiah's pleasant dream.</p>",
"27": "<p>The promise — <strong>I will sow the house of Israel and the house of Judah with the seed of men and the seed of beasts</strong> — is the replanting of the people and the land after the devastation. The seed/sowing imagery runs through the NT as a Christological motif: the Parable of the Sower (Matt 13:3-23) describes the divine word as seed; John 12:24 uses the dying grain as the image of Christ's death and resurrection. The replanting of Israel that Jeremiah announces is the agricultural form of the resurrection hope — out of the dead soil of exile, new life springs through divine initiative.</p>",
"28": "<p>The reversal promise — <strong>as I have watched over them to pluck up and to break down, to overthrow and to destroy and to bring harm, so I will watch over them to build and to plant</strong> — is the direct reversal of the prophet's own commission in 1:10 (&quot;to pluck up and to pull down, to destroy and to overthrow, to build and to plant&quot;). The same divine intentionality that brought judgment will now bring restoration. Paul applies this reversal to the cross: &quot;he who was delivered up for our transgressions was raised for our justification&quot; (Rom 4:25). The same God who brought the death of judgment is the same who brings the life of resurrection.</p>",
"29": "<p>The abolition of the <strong>sour grapes proverb</strong> — &quot;the fathers have eaten sour grapes and the children's teeth are set on edge&quot; — announces a new era of direct individual accountability (paralleled in Ezek 18). The NT develops the tension between corporate solidarity and individual accountability through the lens of Christ: in Adam, all die (corporate solidarity with humanity's fall); in Christ, each one who believes is individually justified (Rom 5:12-21). The proverb's abolition points to the day when each individual stands directly before YHWH — which the NT identifies as the final judgment before Christ (2 Cor 5:10).</p>",
"30": "<p>The positive statement — <strong>everyone who eats the sour grapes, his own teeth will be set on edge; everyone shall die for his own iniquity</strong> — establishes individual moral responsibility as the governing principle. This is the justice principle that the cross both upholds and transcends: Christ's atonement is not an evasion of individual accountability but its satisfaction — the penalty each person deserved was borne by the one who bore it representatively (2 Cor 5:21; 1 Pet 3:18). Individual responsibility is taken with full seriousness, and precisely because it is, the cross is costly.</p>",
"32": "<p>The new covenant's second element — <strong>not like the covenant I made with their fathers when I took them out of Egypt, which they broke though I was a husband to them</strong> — establishes the contrast with the Sinai covenant. Hebrews 8:9 quotes this verse as the ground for arguing that the Levitical priesthood was provisional: the old covenant that was broken required a new covenant. The point is not that YHWH failed but that the external-law covenant was by design provisional — a tutor (Gal 3:24-25) that pointed forward to the internal-law covenant inaugurated by Christ's Spirit-giving ministry.</p>",
"33": "<p>The new covenant's third element — <strong>I will put my law within them and write it on their hearts; I will be their God and they shall be my people</strong> — is the heart of the new covenant promise. Paul quotes this in 2 Corinthians 3:3: &quot;you are a letter from Christ... written not with ink but with the Spirit of the living God, not on tablets of stone but on tablets of human hearts.&quot; The internalization of the law is the Spirit's work: Romans 8:4 says the righteous requirement of the law is fulfilled in those who walk by the Spirit. The new covenant is inaugurated by Christ and implemented by the Spirit he gives.</p>",
"34": "<p>The new covenant's fourth element — <strong>I will forgive their iniquity and I will remember their sin no more</strong> — is the ultimate basis for the entire covenant. Hebrews 10:17-18 quotes this verse as the proof that the new covenant has made the old sacrificial system obsolete: &quot;where there is forgiveness of these, there is no longer any offering for sin.&quot; The permanent, non-recalled forgiveness is what makes the new covenant genuinely new — not a temporary covering (as the Levitical sacrifices were) but a definitive removal. Christ's once-for-all sacrifice is the event that produces this permanent forgiveness (Heb 9:26; 10:14).</p>",
"35": "<p>The cosmic guarantees — <strong>if this fixed order of the sun, moon, and stars departs from before me, then the offspring of Israel shall cease to be a nation before me</strong> — grounds covenant faithfulness in the stability of creation. Paul applies this logic to the irrevocability of God's gifts in Romans 11:29: &quot;the gifts and calling of God are irrevocable.&quot; The cosmic-stability argument establishes that the new covenant is as permanent as creation itself — and ultimately, Christ is the one through whom all things hold together (Col 1:17), so the guarantor of the covenant is the one who sustains the cosmos.</p>",
"36": "<p>The extension of the cosmic guarantee — <strong>if the heavens above can be measured and the foundations of the earth below can be explored, I will cast off all the offspring of Israel for all they have done</strong> — is YHWH's emphatic no to Israel's permanent rejection. Paul's &quot;Has God rejected his people? By no means!&quot; (Rom 11:1) is the direct NT answer to the question this verse implicitly raises. The immeasurability of the heavens guarantees the indefeasibility of the covenant — which the NT locates in Christ as the one in whom all the promises are Yes (2 Cor 1:20).</p>",
"37": "<p>The promise to <strong>rebuild Jerusalem from the Tower of Hananel to the Corner Gate</strong> — the specific geographical markers of the city's restoration — points to the eschatological city. Revelation 21:10-21 describes the New Jerusalem descending from heaven, with specific dimensions and gates — the spiritual fulfillment of Jeremiah's geographical promise. The rebuilt city of Jeremiah 31 is a historical type of the eternal city built by God, whose builder and maker is God (Heb 11:10).</p>",
"38": "<p>The measuring line that goes <strong>straight to the hill Gareb and then shall turn to Goah</strong> — specific restoration geography for areas that were garbage dumps and waste places outside the walls — is the expansion of the holy city into previously defiled areas. The NT redemption of &quot;unclean&quot; areas is the theme of Acts 10-11 (the Gentile mission breaking purity barriers) and Revelation 21:27 (the New Jerusalem where nothing impure can enter precisely because impurity has been removed). The desolate places become holy places in the eschatological city.</p>",
"39": "<p>The valley of dead bodies and ashes — <strong>the whole valley of the dead bodies and ashes, and all the fields as far as the brook Kidron</strong> — being made holy to YHWH represents the transformation of the place of death and defilement into sacred space. The Kidron Valley is where Jesus crossed on his way to Gethsemane (John 18:1) — the last boundary before his arrest and death. The valley associated with death and defilement becomes the path of the Son of God going to his atoning death, transforming the place of death into the ground of life.</p>",
"40": "<p>The final promise — <strong>it shall not be plucked up or overthrown anymore forever</strong> — is the seal of permanence on the new Jerusalem. Revelation 21:4: &quot;death shall be no more, neither shall there be mourning, nor crying, nor pain anymore, for the former things have passed away.&quot; The city that shall never again be plucked up or overthrown is the eternal city of God, whose permanence is secured not by political strength but by the permanent atonement of Christ and the permanent presence of God. The &quot;forever&quot; of the new Jerusalem finds its guarantee in the &quot;forever&quot; of Christ's priesthood (Heb 7:24) and resurrection (Rom 6:9).</p>"
},
"32": {
"1": "<p>The temporal marker — <strong>the word came to Jeremiah in the tenth year of Zedekiah, which was the eighteenth year of Nebuchadnezzar</strong> — situates this oracle at the lowest point of the Babylonian siege. YHWH speaks his most hopeful message precisely when the situation is most desperate. The NT pattern matches: the gospel's most radical proclamation of hope (resurrection, eternal life) is delivered from the cross — the moment of maximum apparent defeat. The word of God comes not when circumstances are favorable but in defiance of circumstances.</p>",
"2": "<p>The army of Babylon besieging Jerusalem while <strong>Jeremiah the prophet was shut up in the court of the guard</strong> — the prophet imprisoned while the enemy advances — is the pattern of truth-telling under persecution. Paul writes his most hopeful letters from prison (Philippians, Ephesians, Colossians); the persecuted community of Hebrews 11 acts on faith in things not seen. The imprisoned prophet prefigures the apostolic witness: &quot;the word of God is not bound&quot; (2 Tim 2:9) even when its messengers are.</p>",
"3": "<p>Zedekiah's charge that <strong>Jeremiah prophesied: YHWH will give this city into the hand of the king of Babylon</strong> — the accusation that the prophet's truth is treasonous. Jesus faces the same accusation: the religious authorities charge that his message undermines the nation's survival (John 11:50: &quot;it is better for one man to die for the people than for the whole nation to perish&quot;). The prophetic word that tells unpleasant truth is always accused of disloyalty; the NT resolves the tension by showing that the one who speaks truth is the one who saves, not destroys.</p>",
"4": "<p>The prophecy that <strong>Zedekiah will be given into the hand of the king of Babylon and speak face to face with him</strong> — the covenant king handed over to the pagan king — is the judgment on unfaithful leadership. The NT has its counterpart: Jesus is handed over by the religious authorities to the Roman governor (Matt 27:2); Pilate speaks with him face to face. But where Zedekiah was taken captive, Jesus's &quot;handover&quot; is the voluntary self-giving of the Son to accomplish redemption (John 10:17-18; Gal 2:20).</p>",
"5": "<p>Zedekiah taken to Babylon until <strong>YHWH attends to him</strong> — the waiting in captivity for divine visitation. The phrase &quot;until YHWH attends to him&quot; (<em>ʿad pqodd oto YHWH</em>) is the language of divine visitation/attention. Luke 1:68 uses the same concept: &quot;Blessed be the Lord God of Israel, for he has visited and redeemed his people.&quot; The divine &quot;visiting&quot; (<em>epeskepsato</em>) that Zechariah celebrates in the Benedictus is the fulfillment of every &quot;until YHWH attends to&quot; in the OT prophets. Christ's coming is the great divine visitation.</p>",
"6": "<p>The word of YHWH coming to Jeremiah — <strong>Hanamel son of your uncle Shallum will come to you</strong> — is a prophetic foreknowledge that establishes the sign-act as YHWH-directed. The foreknowledge of the prophets is a type of the omniscience Christ exercises: &quot;Jesus, knowing that the Father had given all things into his hands&quot; (John 13:3); he foretells Judas's betrayal (John 13:21-27), Peter's denial (John 13:38), and the destruction of the temple (Matt 24:2). The prophet's foreknowledge is a partial and delegated form of the divine omniscience fully expressed in Christ.</p>",
"7": "<p>The right of <strong>redemption and purchase</strong> belonging to Jeremiah — the kinsman-redeemer obligation (<em>gaʾulah</em>) — is the legal mechanism that drives the sign-act. The <em>goʾel</em> (kinsman-redeemer) is one of the richest OT types of Christ: Boaz redeeming Ruth (Ruth 4:1-12), the <em>goʾel</em> of Job 19:25 (&quot;I know that my Redeemer lives&quot;). Christ is the kinsman-redeemer of humanity — becoming flesh to stand in kinship with humanity and exercise the right of redemption on behalf of those who had forfeited their inheritance through sin (Gal 4:4-5; Heb 2:14-17).</p>",
"8": "<p>Hanamel's arrival confirming the word — <strong>then I knew that this was the word of YHWH</strong> — establishes the sign-act as genuine prophetic action. The prophetic word fulfilled in historical event is the pattern of biblical revelation. The NT presents Jesus's fulfillment of OT prophecy as the authentication of his messianic identity: Matthew's formula &quot;this was to fulfill what was spoken by the prophet&quot; applies this verification logic repeatedly (Matt 1:22; 2:17; 4:14; etc.). Historical fulfillment of prophetic word is the mark of genuine revelation.</p>",
"9": "<p>Jeremiah <strong>weighing seventeen shekels of silver</strong> for the field — the precise financial transaction documented in a crisis context — is the detail that makes the sign-act concrete. The purchase of the field with silver during a siege is the enacted parable of faith in future restoration when present evidence points only to loss. The thirty pieces of silver for which Judas sold Jesus (Matt 26:15) — echoing Zechariah 11:12-13 — is a dark mirror of this field-purchase: where Jeremiah's silver secured a hopeful future, Judas's silver secured the arrest of the one who would accomplish the true restoration.</p>",
"10": "<p>The <strong>deed of purchase signed and sealed and witnessed</strong> — the full legal formality of an irrevocable property transaction — is the sign of covenant seriousness. The NT uses the legal-seal image for the Spirit: &quot;you were sealed with the promised Holy Spirit, who is the guarantee of our inheritance&quot; (Eph 1:13-14). The sealed deed of Jeremiah's field purchase is a type of the Spirit as the seal and down-payment on the eschatological inheritance — the legal guarantee of the promised land that cannot be voided.</p>",
"11": "<p>The two copies of the deed — <strong>the sealed copy containing the terms and the open copy</strong> — the sealed and the open portions of the ancient land deed, preserved as legal documentation. The image of a sealed and opened document recurs in Revelation 5:1-9: the seven-sealed scroll that only the Lamb is worthy to open — the title deed of creation itself, held by the one who redeems what was lost. Jeremiah's sealed deed of his field purchase is a type of Christ's claim to and redemption of the whole creation.</p>",
"12": "<p>The deed given to <strong>Baruch son of Neriah</strong> in the presence of witnesses — Jeremiah's personal secretary receiving the legal document. Baruch is the faithful scribe who serves as the prophetic word's custodian. The NT parallel is the apostolic community as scribes and witnesses: &quot;we are witnesses of all that he did&quot; (Acts 10:39); &quot;what we have seen and heard we proclaim to you&quot; (1 John 1:3). The faithful preservation and transmission of the prophetic word is the task of the community of witnesses.</p>",
"13": "<p>The command to <strong>Baruch before all who witnessed the signing: take these deeds, both the sealed and the open, and put them in an earthen vessel, that they may last for a long time</strong> — the preservation of the documents for future generations. The earthen vessel that preserves the documents of hope is the type Paul uses in 2 Corinthians 4:7: &quot;we have this treasure in jars of clay, to show that the surpassing power belongs to God and not to us.&quot; The gospel of the new covenant, like the deed of Jeremiah's field, is carried in earthen vessels and preserved across time for those who will inherit the promise.</p>",
"14": "<p>The purpose of the preservation — <strong>that they may last for a long time</strong> — is faith directed at a future generation. Hebrews 11:13: &quot;these all died in faith, not having received the things promised, but having seen them and greeted them from afar.&quot; The deeds sealed and stored for future use are the structure of prophetic faith: acting now on a promise whose fulfillment lies beyond the current actor's lifetime. The church, bearing the promises of the new covenant, lives in the same structure — possessing the deeds but awaiting the full possession of the inheritance.</p>",
"15": "<p>The sign-act's declared meaning — <strong>houses and fields and vineyards shall again be bought in this land</strong> — is the promise of restored normal life after the catastrophe. The resurrection of normal human life under divine blessing is the eschatological hope the NT presents in creation-renewal terms: Romans 8:21 (&quot;the creation itself will be set free from its bondage to corruption and obtain the freedom of the glory of the children of God&quot;). The future buying of fields and vineyards is the concrete OT expression of what Paul calls the &quot;restoration of all things&quot; (Acts 3:21) and Revelation calls the &quot;new earth&quot; (Rev 21:1).</p>",
"16": "<p>Jeremiah's prayer after the transaction — <strong>after I had given the deed to Baruch, I prayed to YHWH</strong> — shows the prophet immediately turning the sign-act into prayer. The pattern of act-then-prayer mirrors Jesus's own practice: after feeding the five thousand (John 6:11-15), after healing (Luke 5:16), before the cross (John 17). The prophetic sign-act is not complete until the human agent brings it before YHWH in prayer — the external act and the internal communion belong together.</p>",
"17": "<p>The opening of the prayer — <strong>Ah, Lord YHWH! It is you who have made the heavens and the earth by your great power and by your outstretched arm. Nothing is too hard for you</strong> — grounds the prophetic hope in creation-theology. The &quot;nothing too hard&quot; (<em>lo yipalleʾ davar</em>) echoes Genesis 18:14 (God's word to Sarah about Isaac: &quot;Is anything too hard for YHWH?&quot;). Luke 1:37 applies the same logic to the virgin birth: &quot;nothing will be impossible with God.&quot; The omnipotence of the creator God is the logical ground for miraculous intervention — applied by Gabriel to the incarnation as by YHWH to Sarah's pregnancy.</p>",
"18": "<p>The prayer's recollection of <strong>YHWH showing steadfast love to thousands, but repaying the guilt of fathers to their children after them</strong> — the covenant formula of Exodus 20:5-6, here cited in context of intercession. Jesus does not quote this retributive half of the covenant formula; he instead emphasizes the mercy (&quot;seventy times seven&quot;, Matt 18:22). But the NT does not abandon the covenant justice — rather, Christ's cross is where the full weight of covenant guilt is absorbed, so that the &quot;visiting iniquity&quot; falls on the Son rather than on later generations (2 Cor 5:21; Gal 3:13).</p>",
"19": "<p>YHWH's <strong>great counsel and mighty works, whose eyes are open to all the ways of all mankind</strong> — divine omniscience applied to history. The &quot;great counsel&quot; (<em>gadol haʿetsah</em>) is the divine plan that encompasses all of history. Ephesians 1:11 describes this as the &quot;plan of him who works all things according to the counsel of his will.&quot; The &quot;mystery of his will&quot; that Paul reveals is Christ as the center of all history — the one in whom the &quot;great counsel&quot; of Jeremiah's prayer is focused and fulfilled (Eph 1:9-10).</p>",
"20": "<p>The recollection of <strong>signs and wonders in Egypt and to this day, in Israel and among all mankind</strong> — the Exodus miracles as the paradigm of divine saving power. Peter's Pentecost sermon (Acts 2:22) applies the same paradigm to Jesus: &quot;a man attested to you by God with mighty works and wonders and signs.&quot; The Exodus signs and wonders that Jeremiah's prayer recalls are the framework within which the NT presents Christ's miracles as the new-Exodus signs of the messianic age. Jesus's miracles are not isolated marvels but signs of the new Exodus.</p>",
"21": "<p>The specific recollection — <strong>you brought your people Israel out of Egypt with signs and wonders, with a strong hand and outstretched arm, and with great terror</strong> — is the creedal Exodus formula (Deut 26:8). Hebrews 3:1-6 presents Jesus as greater than Moses, who led the first Exodus — Jesus is the Son over the house that Moses only served in. The outstretched arm that brought Israel out of Egypt is the same power that raised Jesus from the dead (Eph 1:19-20). The Exodus formula is christologically reappropriated across the NT.</p>",
"22": "<p>The inheritance given — <strong>you gave them this land that you swore to their fathers to give them, a land flowing with milk and honey</strong> — is the covenant promise fulfilled in the land. Hebrews 4:8-11 interprets the land-rest typologically: Joshua gave the physical rest, but the Sabbath rest that remains for the people of God is the spiritual rest Christ provides. The &quot;land flowing with milk and honey&quot; is a type of the &quot;better country&quot; (Heb 11:16) that the patriarchs sought and which is fulfilled in the heavenly city whose builder and maker is God.</p>",
"23": "<p>The contrast — <strong>they entered and took possession of it, but they did not obey your voice or walk in your law</strong> — establishes the tragic gap between possession of the gift and obedience to the giver. Paul's analysis of Israel in Romans 9-11 engages exactly this paradox: Israel received the adoption, the glory, the covenants, the law, the worship, the promises, and the patriarchs — yet the majority did not believe (Rom 9:4-7). The failure of covenant obedience despite covenant gift establishes the need for the new covenant, where obedience is not demanded from without but written within by the Spirit.</p>",
"24": "<p>The report of the siege mounds — <strong>the siege mounds have come up to the city to take it, and the city is given into the hands of the Chaldeans</strong> — while Jeremiah prays, the catastrophe is unfolding in real time. The prayer offered in the midst of visible disaster is the pattern of NT faith: Paul praying in prison (Phil 4:6-7); the disciples praying during Herod's persecution (Acts 12:5); Revelation's prayers of the saints ascending as incense even as judgment unfolds (Rev 8:3-4). Faith and prayer are not alternatives to facing reality but the posture in which reality is faced.</p>",
"25": "<p>Jeremiah's perplexity — <strong>yet you, O Lord YHWH, have said to me: Buy the field for money and get witnesses — though the city is given into the hands of the Chaldeans</strong> — is the honest naming of the apparent absurdity: God commanded the purchase of land that was about to be lost. This is the structure of faith described in Hebrews 11:1: &quot;the substance of things hoped for, the evidence of things not seen.&quot; The purchase of the apparently worthless field is the enacted parable of what the NT calls faith — acting on the divine word in defiance of visible evidence.</p>",
"26": "<p>YHWH's response beginning with the divine self-identification — <strong>the word of YHWH came to Jeremiah: Behold, I am YHWH, the God of all flesh</strong> — reasserts divine sovereignty over all of human life. The claim &quot;God of all flesh&quot; (<em>ʾElohei kol-basar</em>) is the foundation for the universal scope of the new covenant. Paul argues in Romans 3:29-30: &quot;Is God the God of Jews only? Is he not the God of Gentiles also? Yes, of Gentiles also, since God is one.&quot; The God who is God of all flesh is the God whose new covenant, through Christ, is for all nations.</p>",
"27": "<p><strong>Is anything too hard for me?</strong> — the divine rhetorical question echoing 17b and Genesis 18:14, here applied directly to the restoration promise. Matthew 19:26: &quot;With man this is impossible, but with God all things are possible.&quot; The resurrection is the definitive answer to this question: what was impossible for human hope — the reversal of death — YHWH accomplished in Christ. Every instance of &quot;is anything too hard for me?&quot; in the OT is answered finally and permanently by Easter morning.</p>",
"28": "<p>The oracle — <strong>I will give this city into the hands of the Chaldeans and Nebuchadnezzar</strong> — is the confirmation that the judgment is real and will be executed. The judgment that Jeremiah announces is not softened by the purchase of the field; both truths coexist: judgment is coming and restoration is coming. The NT holds the same tension: Romans 11:22 (&quot;note then the kindness and the severity of God&quot;) — the cross simultaneously enacts the severity of judgment and the kindness of redemption. Both are real; neither cancels the other.</p>",
"29": "<p>The burning of the houses <strong>on whose rooftops offerings were made to Baal and drink offerings were poured out to other gods, to provoke me to anger</strong> — the specific covenant violations that brought the specific covenant curse of fire. The NT uses fire as the image of judgment on false worship: Revelation 17-18 describes the burning of Babylon, the city of false religion. The judgment of fire on the rooftop altars of Baal is the historical type of the eschatological judgment on all idolatrous systems. Christ's return brings the definitive burning of all that is opposed to the living God.</p>",
"30": "<p>The summary of accumulated sin — <strong>the people of Israel and Judah have done nothing but evil in my sight from their youth</strong> — is the verdict of universal covenant failure. This matches Paul's summary in Romans 3:10-18: &quot;there is no one righteous, not even one... all have turned aside.&quot; The comprehensive failure of Israel and Judah is not exceptional but representative — the corruption of the covenant people reflects the universal human condition. This establishes the scope of what Christ's redemption must address: not a minor reform but a comprehensive new creation.</p>",
"31": "<p>The specific enumeration — <strong>this city has aroused my anger and wrath, from the day it was built to this day, so that I will remove it from my sight</strong> — is the accumulated weight of covenant violation from the very beginning. The &quot;from the day it was built&quot; mirrors the &quot;from your youth&quot; of v30: the problem is congenital, not episodic. The NT diagnosis is the same: the law brought knowledge of sin but not its cure (Rom 3:20; Gal 3:10). The deep-rootedness of the problem is what makes the new covenant's radical solution (new heart, indwelling Spirit) necessary rather than merely sufficient.</p>",
"32": "<p>The catalog of covenant violation — <strong>the kings and officials, the priests and prophets, the men of Judah and the inhabitants of Jerusalem</strong> — encompasses all social classes and offices. No one is exempt from the indictment; every stratum of society participated in the covenant failure. Romans 3:23 states the same universality: &quot;for all have sinned and fall short of the glory of God.&quot; The comprehensive scope of the accusation matches the comprehensive scope of the solution: &quot;all who believe&quot; (Rom 3:22), &quot;all nations&quot; (Matt 28:19), &quot;every tongue&quot; (Phil 2:11).</p>",
"33": "<p>The people <strong>turning their back to me and not their face; I have taught them persistently but they have not listened</strong> — the divine teacher refused by the student. Jesus laments the same: &quot;O Jerusalem, Jerusalem, the city that kills the prophets... how often would I have gathered your children together as a hen gathers her brood under her wings, and you were not willing!&quot; (Matt 23:37). The unwillingness to receive divine instruction is the core problem, and the new covenant's solution — law written on the heart — is precisely its solution: those who have been given a new heart will not turn their backs.</p>",
"34": "<p>The high places of Baal in <strong>the Valley of Hinnom, to offer their sons and daughters to Molech</strong> — the child-sacrifice that was the extreme form of covenant violation. The Valley of Hinnom (Ge-hinnom, Gehenna) becomes in the NT the image for eschatological judgment (Mark 9:43-48; Matt 5:22). Jesus's use of Gehenna to describe the eschatological fire draws on this location where children were burned as offerings — the ultimate perversion of covenant worship. The place of covenant horror becomes the image of eschatological judgment.</p>",
"35": "<p>YHWH's declaration that <strong>I did not command them, nor did it enter my mind, that they should do this abomination</strong> — the explicit repudiation of child sacrifice as having any divine sanction. The NT fulfillment inverts this: God does give his own Son, not as a burnt offering forced by foreign religion, but as the willing self-sacrifice of love (John 3:16; Rom 8:32). What the pagan nations did to their children by compulsion and with divine repudiation, the Father does with his Son willingly and lovingly — the difference being infinite, as love differs from murder.</p>",
"36": "<p>The transition from judgment to restoration — <strong>now therefore, thus says the Lord, the God of Israel, concerning this city of which you say: it is given into the hand of the king of Babylon through sword, famine, and pestilence</strong> — the &quot;now therefore&quot; pivot that turns from accusation to promise. The rhetorical pivot from &quot;you have sinned&quot; to &quot;here is my promise&quot; is the structure of the gospel: &quot;but God demonstrates his love for us in that while we were still sinners, Christ died for us&quot; (Rom 5:8). The gospel's &quot;but God&quot; is the NT version of Jeremiah's &quot;now therefore.&quot;</p>",
"37": "<p>The promise — <strong>I will gather them from all the lands to which I drove them in my anger and great wrath, and I will bring them back to this place and let them dwell in safety</strong> — is the diaspora-gathering promise. The NT fulfillment is Pentecost (Acts 2:5-11 — Jews from every nation gathered in Jerusalem) and the worldwide mission gathering from every nation into the one body of Christ. Ephesians 2:14-18: Christ &quot;has made us both one and has broken down in his flesh the dividing wall of hostility... creating in himself one new man.&quot;</p>",
"38": "<p>The new covenant formula — <strong>they shall be my people and I will be their God; I will give them one heart and one way, that they may fear me forever</strong> — combines the covenant-formula (&quot;my people/their God&quot;) with the new-covenant element of internal unity (&quot;one heart and one way&quot;). Philippians 2:2: &quot;complete my joy by being of the same mind, having the same love, being in full accord and of one mind.&quot; The unity of heart that Jeremiah promises is the unity of the community in Christ — achieved not by external pressure but by the Spirit's unifying work in those who share one Lord, one faith, one baptism (Eph 4:3-6).</p>",
"39": "<p>The promise that <strong>I will put the fear of me in their hearts, that they may not turn from me</strong> — the internalized reverence that produces permanent fidelity, replacing the externally commanded but internally unfelt covenant obedience. Romans 8:15: &quot;you did not receive the spirit of slavery to fall back into fear, but you have received the Spirit of adoption.&quot; The &quot;fear&quot; that the new covenant instills is not slavish terror but the reverent love of an adopted child — the Spirit of sonship who produces the genuine devotion that the old covenant demanded but could not produce.</p>",
"40": "<p>A <strong>direct type</strong>: <strong>I will make with them an everlasting covenant (<em>berit ʿolam</em>), that I will not turn away from doing good to them; I will put the fear of me in their hearts, that they may not turn from me</strong>. Hebrews 13:20-21 applies the &quot;everlasting covenant&quot; to Christ's resurrection: &quot;the God of peace who brought again from the dead our Lord Jesus Christ, by the blood of the eternal covenant, equip you with everything good that you may do his will.&quot; The &quot;everlasting covenant&quot; of Jeremiah 32 is identified as the covenant whose blood is Christ's, enacted by his resurrection. This is one of the clearest NT identifications of the new covenant with the person and work of Christ.</p>",
"41": "<p>The joy of restoration — <strong>I will rejoice in doing them good, and I will plant them in this land in faithfulness, with all my heart and all my soul</strong> — is YHWH declaring that the restoration will not be reluctant or minimal but wholehearted. The divine &quot;with all my heart and all my soul&quot; is the measure of covenant commitment. Zephaniah 3:17 matches it: &quot;YHWH your God is in your midst, a mighty one who will save; he will rejoice over you with gladness; he will quiet you by his love; he will exult over you with loud singing.&quot; In Christ, this divine joy over the restored covenant people is made flesh and manifested.</p>",
"42": "<p>The assurance — <strong>as I have brought all this great disaster on this people, so I will bring on them all the good that I promise them</strong> — uses the certainty of the past disaster as the measure of the certainty of the future blessing. Paul applies the same logic: &quot;he who did not spare his own Son but gave him up for us all — how will he not also with him graciously give us all things?&quot; (Rom 8:32). The cross — the greatest disaster from one perspective — is the guarantee of the greatest blessing from another. The measure of God's severity becomes the measure of his grace.</p>",
"43": "<p>The sign enacted — <strong>fields shall be bought in this land of which you are saying: it is a desolation, without man or beast; it is given into the hand of the Chaldeans</strong> — is the purchase carried out in defiance of the present reality. The structure of the sign-act is the structure of Christian baptism: the baptized person claims death and resurrection as their present reality in defiance of visible appearance. &quot;You have died, and your life is hidden with Christ in God&quot; (Col 3:3) — present claim, future visible vindication. The field purchase is faith-in-action against present evidence.</p>",
"44": "<p>The comprehensive scope of the restoration — <strong>fields shall be bought for money, deeds signed and sealed and witnessed, in the land of Benjamin, in the places around Jerusalem, in the cities of Judah, the cities of the hill country, the cities of the lowland, and the cities of the Negeb</strong> — covers every region of the land. The final verse's geographical completeness is the picture of total restoration from which nothing is excluded. The NT counterpart is Revelation 21:5: &quot;Behold, I am making all things new.&quot; The comprehensive restoration of every region of the land is a type of the comprehensive new creation that Christ accomplishes — where every dimension of the broken creation is restored, not just repaired at the edges.</p>"
}
}

